<subSubSection lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="421" pageId="4" pageNumber="418" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1389,2027]" box="[199,978,1533,1559]" pageId="4" pageNumber="418">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,1533,1559]" pageId="4" pageNumber="418">Description</emphasis>
. Female. Body length 
<quantity box="[593,682,1533,1559]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.6" pageId="4" pageNumber="418" unit="mm" value="4.6">4.6 mm</quantity>
; fore wing length 
<quantity box="[885,974,1533,1559]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.2" pageId="4" pageNumber="418" unit="mm" value="3.2">3.2 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1389,2027]" pageId="4" pageNumber="418">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,263,1569,1595]" pageId="4" pageNumber="418">Head</emphasis>
. Head width 1.2 × its height in anterior view (
<figureCitation box="[788,877,1569,1595]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetId="figure-200@5.[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Symplecis anaeratabettensis sp. nov., holotype, female A) habitus, lateral view; B) head, anterior view; C) head, dorsal view; D) head, antero-ventral view; E) head &amp; mesosoma, lateral view; F) mesosoma (in part), dorsal view." pageId="4" pageNumber="418">Fig. 3B</figureCitation>
). Face width at level of antennal sockets 1.1 × its height, 0.4 × width of head, smooth and polished, sparsely setose (
<figureCitation box="[921,1011,1605,1631]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetId="figure-200@5.[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Symplecis anaeratabettensis sp. nov., holotype, female A) habitus, lateral view; B) head, anterior view; C) head, dorsal view; D) head, antero-ventral view; E) head &amp; mesosoma, lateral view; F) mesosoma (in part), dorsal view." pageId="4" pageNumber="418">Fig. 3B</figureCitation>
). Frons, vertex and occiput polished, sparsely setose (
<figureCitation box="[341,433,1641,1667]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetId="figure-200@5.[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Symplecis anaeratabettensis sp. nov., holotype, female A) habitus, lateral view; B) head, anterior view; C) head, dorsal view; D) head, antero-ventral view; E) head &amp; mesosoma, lateral view; F) mesosoma (in part), dorsal view." pageId="4" pageNumber="418">Fig. 3C</figureCitation>
). Occiput somewhat depressed; occipital carina present (
<figureCitation box="[1095,1187,1641,1667]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetId="figure-200@5.[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Symplecis anaeratabettensis sp. nov., holotype, female A) habitus, lateral view; B) head, anterior view; C) head, dorsal view; D) head, antero-ventral view; E) head &amp; mesosoma, lateral view; F) mesosoma (in part), dorsal view." pageId="4" pageNumber="418">Fig. 3C</figureCitation>
). Eyes large, convex, without setae, inner orbits strongly converge to clypeus (
<figureCitation box="[785,872,1677,1703]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetId="figure-200@5.[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Symplecis anaeratabettensis sp. nov., holotype, female A) habitus, lateral view; B) head, anterior view; C) head, dorsal view; D) head, antero-ventral view; E) head &amp; mesosoma, lateral view; F) mesosoma (in part), dorsal view." pageId="4" pageNumber="418">Fig. 3B</figureCitation>
). Clypeus width 2.7 × its height, weakly separated from face, posterior margin of clypeus very weakly convex (
<figureCitation box="[838,927,1713,1739]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetId="figure-200@5.[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Symplecis anaeratabettensis sp. nov., holotype, female A) habitus, lateral view; B) head, anterior view; C) head, dorsal view; D) head, antero-ventral view; E) head &amp; mesosoma, lateral view; F) mesosoma (in part), dorsal view." pageId="4" pageNumber="418">Fig. 3B</figureCitation>
). Anterior tentorial pits distinct (
<figureCitation box="[1299,1424,1713,1739]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetId="figure-200@5.[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Symplecis anaeratabettensis sp. nov., holotype, female A) habitus, lateral view; B) head, anterior view; C) head, dorsal view; D) head, antero-ventral view; E) head &amp; mesosoma, lateral view; F) mesosoma (in part), dorsal view." pageId="4" pageNumber="418">Fig. 3B, D</figureCitation>
). Malar space very short, 0.6 × as long as basal width of mandible (
<figureCitation box="[917,1007,1749,1775]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetId="figure-200@5.[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Symplecis anaeratabettensis sp. nov., holotype, female A) habitus, lateral view; B) head, anterior view; C) head, dorsal view; D) head, antero-ventral view; E) head &amp; mesosoma, lateral view; F) mesosoma (in part), dorsal view." pageId="4" pageNumber="418">Fig. 3B</figureCitation>
). Subocular sulcus present. Mandible bidentate, strongly tapered, lower tooth small (
<figureCitation box="[676,767,1785,1811]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetId="figure-200@5.[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Symplecis anaeratabettensis sp. nov., holotype, female A) habitus, lateral view; B) head, anterior view; C) head, dorsal view; D) head, antero-ventral view; E) head &amp; mesosoma, lateral view; F) mesosoma (in part), dorsal view." pageId="4" pageNumber="418">Fig. 3D</figureCitation>
). Antenna shorter than body, with 18 slender flagellomeres, all flagellomeres longer than wide (
<figureCitation box="[549,639,1821,1847]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetId="figure-200@5.[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Symplecis anaeratabettensis sp. nov., holotype, female A) habitus, lateral view; B) head, anterior view; C) head, dorsal view; D) head, antero-ventral view; E) head &amp; mesosoma, lateral view; F) mesosoma (in part), dorsal view." pageId="4" pageNumber="418">Fig. 3A</figureCitation>
). Scape about twice as long as wide. First flagellomere 5.6 × as long as wide apically, second flagellomere 4.3 × as long as wide apically. Ocelli of moderate size, ocular-ocellar line 1.2 × and postocellar line 1.1 × as long as maximum diameter of lateral ocellus (
<figureCitation box="[980,1068,1893,1919]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetId="figure-200@5.[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Symplecis anaeratabettensis sp. nov., holotype, female A) habitus, lateral view; B) head, anterior view; C) head, dorsal view; D) head, antero-ventral view; E) head &amp; mesosoma, lateral view; F) mesosoma (in part), dorsal view." pageId="4" pageNumber="418">Fig. 3C</figureCitation>
). Temple moderately short, 0.4 × as long as compound eye width (
<figureCitation box="[519,607,1929,1955]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetId="figure-200@5.[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Symplecis anaeratabettensis sp. nov., holotype, female A) habitus, lateral view; B) head, anterior view; C) head, dorsal view; D) head, antero-ventral view; E) head &amp; mesosoma, lateral view; F) mesosoma (in part), dorsal view." pageId="4" pageNumber="418">Fig. 3C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1389,2027]" lastBlockId="5.[151,1437,151,501]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="419" pageId="4" pageNumber="418">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,325,1965,1991]" pageId="4" pageNumber="418">Mesosoma</emphasis>
. Mesosoma 1.4 × as long as maximum height, polished. Epomia well developed (
<figureCitation box="[1224,1309,1965,1991]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetId="figure-200@5.[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Symplecis anaeratabettensis sp. nov., holotype, female A) habitus, lateral view; B) head, anterior view; C) head, dorsal view; D) head, antero-ventral view; E) head &amp; mesosoma, lateral view; F) mesosoma (in part), dorsal view." pageId="4" pageNumber="418">Fig. 3E</figureCitation>
). Mesoscutum subpolished with dense light setae, lateral lobes of mesoscutum slightly rugose (
<figureCitation box="[1085,1169,2001,2027]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetId="figure-200@5.[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Symplecis anaeratabettensis sp. nov., holotype, female A) habitus, lateral view; B) head, anterior view; C) head, dorsal view; D) head, antero-ventral view; E) head &amp; mesosoma, lateral view; F) mesosoma (in part), dorsal view." pageId="4" pageNumber="418">Fig. 3F</figureCitation>
). Notauli comparatively short, posteriorly shallow, developed in anterior 1/3 of mesoscutum, not meeting (
<figureCitation box="[1048,1131,151,177]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetId="figure-200@5.[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Symplecis anaeratabettensis sp. nov., holotype, female A) habitus, lateral view; B) head, anterior view; C) head, dorsal view; D) head, antero-ventral view; E) head &amp; mesosoma, lateral view; F) mesosoma (in part), dorsal view." pageId="5" pageNumber="419">Fig. 3F</figureCitation>
). Scutellum not particularly high, smooth, with lateral carinae anteriorly (
<figureCitation box="[650,735,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetId="figure-200@5.[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Symplecis anaeratabettensis sp. nov., holotype, female A) habitus, lateral view; B) head, anterior view; C) head, dorsal view; D) head, antero-ventral view; E) head &amp; mesosoma, lateral view; F) mesosoma (in part), dorsal view." pageId="5" pageNumber="419">Fig. 3F</figureCitation>
). Epicnemial carina complete, developed up mid-height of pronotum and not reaching front side of mesopleuron (
<figureCitation box="[717,802,223,249]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetId="figure-200@5.[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Symplecis anaeratabettensis sp. nov., holotype, female A) habitus, lateral view; B) head, anterior view; C) head, dorsal view; D) head, antero-ventral view; E) head &amp; mesosoma, lateral view; F) mesosoma (in part), dorsal view." pageId="5" pageNumber="419">Fig. 3E</figureCitation>
). Sternaulus short, 0.35 of mesopleuron, but distinct (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetId="figure-200@5.[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Symplecis anaeratabettensis sp. nov., holotype, female A) habitus, lateral view; B) head, anterior view; C) head, dorsal view; D) head, antero-ventral view; E) head &amp; mesosoma, lateral view; F) mesosoma (in part), dorsal view." pageId="5" pageNumber="419">Fig. 3E</figureCitation>
). Mesopleuron polished, sparsely setose (
<figureCitation box="[636,720,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetId="figure-200@5.[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Symplecis anaeratabettensis sp. nov., holotype, female A) habitus, lateral view; B) head, anterior view; C) head, dorsal view; D) head, antero-ventral view; E) head &amp; mesosoma, lateral view; F) mesosoma (in part), dorsal view." pageId="5" pageNumber="419">Fig. 3E</figureCitation>
). Metapleuron faintly sculptured with distinct juxtacoxal and submetapleural carinae, sparsely setose (
<figureCitation box="[557,641,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetId="figure-200@5.[189,1398,525,1932]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Symplecis anaeratabettensis sp. nov., holotype, female A) habitus, lateral view; B) head, anterior view; C) head, dorsal view; D) head, antero-ventral view; E) head &amp; mesosoma, lateral view; F) mesosoma (in part), dorsal view." pageId="5" pageNumber="419">Fig. 3E</figureCitation>
). Propodeum faintly sculptured with complete carination (
<figureCitation box="[1278,1365,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1641,1665]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,181,1617]" captionTargetId="figure-19@6.[177,1411,181,1617]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Symplecis anaeratabettensis sp. nov., holotype, female A) propodeum, dorsal view; B) wings; C) metasoma, lateral view; D) metasoma, dorsal view." pageId="5" pageNumber="419">Fig. 4A</figureCitation>
). Area superomedia comparatively large, narrowing posteriorly, nearly as wide as long (
<figureCitation box="[1045,1134,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1641,1665]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,181,1617]" captionTargetId="figure-19@6.[177,1411,181,1617]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Symplecis anaeratabettensis sp. nov., holotype, female A) propodeum, dorsal view; B) wings; C) metasoma, lateral view; D) metasoma, dorsal view." pageId="5" pageNumber="419">Fig. 4A</figureCitation>
). Propodeal spiracle round, joined by short carina with pleural carina. Fore wing with areolet (
<figureCitation box="[861,947,367,393]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1641,1665]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,181,1617]" captionTargetId="figure-19@6.[177,1411,181,1617]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Symplecis anaeratabettensis sp. nov., holotype, female A) propodeum, dorsal view; B) wings; C) metasoma, lateral view; D) metasoma, dorsal view." pageId="5" pageNumber="419">Fig. 4B</figureCitation>
). Pterostigma 2.5 × as long as wide. Vein 2mcu with two bullae (
<figureCitation box="[367,453,403,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1641,1665]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,181,1617]" captionTargetId="figure-19@6.[177,1411,181,1617]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Symplecis anaeratabettensis sp. nov., holotype, female A) propodeum, dorsal view; B) wings; C) metasoma, lateral view; D) metasoma, dorsal view." pageId="5" pageNumber="419">Fig. 4B</figureCitation>
). Vein 1cu-a interstitial of vein M&amp;RS (
<figureCitation box="[888,974,403,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1641,1665]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,181,1617]" captionTargetId="figure-19@6.[177,1411,181,1617]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Symplecis anaeratabettensis sp. nov., holotype, female A) propodeum, dorsal view; B) wings; C) metasoma, lateral view; D) metasoma, dorsal view." pageId="5" pageNumber="419">Fig. 4B</figureCitation>
). Hind wing with nervellus (CU+cu-a) not intercepted, second abscissa of CU not developed (
<figureCitation box="[703,789,439,465]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1641,1665]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,181,1617]" captionTargetId="figure-19@6.[177,1411,181,1617]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Symplecis anaeratabettensis sp. nov., holotype, female A) propodeum, dorsal view; B) wings; C) metasoma, lateral view; D) metasoma, dorsal view." pageId="5" pageNumber="419">Fig. 4B</figureCitation>
). Hind coxa smooth. Hind femur 5.8 × as long as maximum width. Hind tibia 6.9 × as long as wide. Tibial spurs slender, claws long and thin, moderately bent.
</paragraph>
<caption pageId="5" pageNumber="419" startId="5.[151,250,1956,1980]" targetBox="[189,1398,525,1932]" targetPageId="5">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,1956,2016]" pageId="5" pageNumber="419">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,270,1956,1980]" pageId="5" pageNumber="419">FIGURE 3</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Ranjith &amp; Humala &amp; Priyadarsanan, 2022" authorityName="Ranjith &amp; Humala &amp; Priyadarsanan" authorityYear="2022" box="[283,572,1956,1980]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Symplecis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="419" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anaeratabettensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[283,572,1956,1980]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="419">Symplecis anaeratabettensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[579,660,1956,1980]" pageId="5" pageNumber="419">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[579,660,1956,1980]" pageId="5" pageNumber="419" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, holotype, female A) habitus, lateral view; B) head, anterior view; C) head, dorsal view; D) head, antero-ventral view; E) head &amp; mesosoma, lateral view; F) mesosoma (in part), dorsal view.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption pageId="6" pageNumber="420" startId="6.[151,250,1641,1665]" targetBox="[177,1411,181,1617]" targetPageId="6">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1641,1701]" pageId="6" pageNumber="420">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,270,1641,1665]" pageId="6" pageNumber="420">FIGURE 4</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Ranjith &amp; Humala &amp; Priyadarsanan, 2022" authorityName="Ranjith &amp; Humala &amp; Priyadarsanan" authorityYear="2022" box="[283,572,1641,1665]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Symplecis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="420" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anaeratabettensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[283,572,1641,1665]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="420">Symplecis anaeratabettensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[579,660,1641,1665]" pageId="6" pageNumber="420">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[579,660,1641,1665]" pageId="6" pageNumber="420" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, holotype, female A) propodeum, dorsal view; B) wings; C) metasoma, lateral view; D) metasoma, dorsal view.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1747,2026]" pageId="6" pageNumber="420">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,323,1748,1774]" pageId="6" pageNumber="420">Metasoma</emphasis>
. First metasomal segment 2.6 × as long as maximum width posteriorly, rugose, with basolateral sharp projections (
<figureCitation box="[366,460,1783,1810]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1641,1665]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,181,1617]" captionTargetId="figure-19@6.[177,1411,181,1617]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Symplecis anaeratabettensis sp. nov., holotype, female A) propodeum, dorsal view; B) wings; C) metasoma, lateral view; D) metasoma, dorsal view." pageId="6" pageNumber="420">Fig. 4D</figureCitation>
). Sternite and tergite fused, glymma absent, spiracle situated at apical 0.3 length of T1, apex of first sternite at 0.7 of segment (
<figureCitation box="[649,740,1819,1846]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1641,1665]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,181,1617]" captionTargetId="figure-19@6.[177,1411,181,1617]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Symplecis anaeratabettensis sp. nov., holotype, female A) propodeum, dorsal view; B) wings; C) metasoma, lateral view; D) metasoma, dorsal view." pageId="6" pageNumber="420">Fig. 4C</figureCitation>
). Second metasomal tergite 1.3 × as long as maximum width posteriorly, longitudinally striate, with small round thyridium, smooth and polished in posterior margin (
<figureCitation box="[1332,1424,1855,1882]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1641,1665]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,181,1617]" captionTargetId="figure-19@6.[177,1411,181,1617]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Symplecis anaeratabettensis sp. nov., holotype, female A) propodeum, dorsal view; B) wings; C) metasoma, lateral view; D) metasoma, dorsal view." pageId="6" pageNumber="420">Fig. 4D</figureCitation>
). Remaining tergites smooth, sparsely setose (
<figureCitation box="[649,740,1891,1918]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1641,1665]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,181,1617]" captionTargetId="figure-19@6.[177,1411,181,1617]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Symplecis anaeratabettensis sp. nov., holotype, female A) propodeum, dorsal view; B) wings; C) metasoma, lateral view; D) metasoma, dorsal view." pageId="6" pageNumber="420">Fig. 4D</figureCitation>
). Ovipositor straight without dorsal subapical notch (
<figureCitation box="[1335,1424,1891,1918]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1641,1665]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,181,1617]" captionTargetId="figure-19@6.[177,1411,181,1617]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Symplecis anaeratabettensis sp. nov., holotype, female A) propodeum, dorsal view; B) wings; C) metasoma, lateral view; D) metasoma, dorsal view." pageId="6" pageNumber="420">Fig. 4C</figureCitation>
). Ovipositor sheath 0.4 × as long as first tergite and 0.2 × as long as hind tibia, without setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1747,2026]" lastBlockId="7.[151,1437,151,646]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="421" pageId="6" pageNumber="420">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,283,1963,1989]" pageId="6" pageNumber="420">Colour</emphasis>
. Body black except antennae, legs, mesopleuron, second metasomal tergite posteriorly, anterior and posterior parts of third metasomal tergite, and sixth metasomal tergite, which are yellowish; scape, pedicel, lower frontal orbits, face, clypeus, mandibles, maxillary and labial palps, pronotum, propleuron, tegula, fore and mid coxae and trochanters pale; mesoscutum, scutellum, middle part of third tergite, hypopygium, ovipositor sheath and pterostigma reddish brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,646]" box="[199,392,259,285]" pageId="7" pageNumber="421">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,260,259,285]" pageId="7" pageNumber="421">Male</emphasis>
. Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,422,294,321]" pageId="7" pageNumber="421" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,646]" box="[199,422,294,321]" pageId="7" pageNumber="421">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,289,294,320]" pageId="7" pageNumber="421">Biology</emphasis>
. Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,565,330,358]" pageId="7" pageNumber="421" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,646]" box="[199,565,330,358]" pageId="7" pageNumber="421">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,330,356]" pageId="7" pageNumber="421">Distribution</emphasis>
. 
<collectingCountry box="[359,417,331,357]" name="India" pageId="7" pageNumber="421">India</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[432,554,331,358]" country="India" name="Karnataka" pageId="7" pageNumber="421">Karnataka</collectingRegion>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="421" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,646]" pageId="7" pageNumber="421">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,367,393]" pageId="7" pageNumber="421">Etymology</emphasis>
. The species is named after the 
<typeStatus box="[703,751,367,393]" pageId="7" pageNumber="421">type</typeStatus>
locality, Anaeratabetta, the highest peak in Biligiri Rangaswamy Temple (BRT) Tiger Reserve, which is a hardly disturbed exotic habitat.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,646]" pageId="7" pageNumber="421">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,475,438,464]" pageId="7" pageNumber="421">Comparative diagnosis</emphasis>
. Only one 
<taxonomicName box="[607,812,439,465]" pageId="7" pageNumber="421">
<emphasis box="[607,719,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="421">Symplecis</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Morley, 1913)" baseAuthorityName="Morley" baseAuthorityYear="1913" box="[825,1135,439,465]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Symplecis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="421" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="petiolata">
<emphasis box="[825,955,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="421">S. petiolata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Morley, C." box="[971,1127,439,465]" pageId="7" pageNumber="421" refId="ref4821" refString="Morley, C. (1913) The fauna of British India including Ceylon and Burma, Hymenoptera. Vol. 3. Ichneumonidae. British Museum, London, 531 pp." type="book" year="1913">Morley, 1913</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
has been known from the Indomalayan region (
<collectingCountry box="[393,509,475,502]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="7" pageNumber="421">Sri Lanka</collectingCountry>
). Apart from the differences given in the key, 
<taxonomicName authority="Ranjith &amp; Humala &amp; Priyadarsanan, 2022" authorityName="Ranjith &amp; Humala &amp; Priyadarsanan" authorityYear="2022" box="[1030,1258,475,501]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Symplecis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="421" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anaeratabettensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1030,1258,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="421">S. anaeratabettensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1265,1356,475,501]" pageId="7" pageNumber="421">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1265,1356,475,501]" pageId="7" pageNumber="421" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
differs from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Morley" baseAuthorityYear="1913" box="[214,344,511,537]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Symplecis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="421" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="petiolata">
<emphasis box="[214,344,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="421">S. petiolata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having a longer (
<quantity box="[575,665,510,537]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" pageId="7" pageNumber="421" unit="mm" value="4.5">4.5 mm</quantity>
) body (
<emphasis box="[755,778,511,536]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="421">vs</emphasis>
3.0 mm in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Morley" baseAuthorityYear="1913" box="[913,1042,511,537]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Symplecis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="421" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="petiolata">
<emphasis box="[913,1042,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="421">S. petiolata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), a shorter (2.5 × as long as wide) pterostigma (
<emphasis box="[301,324,547,572]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="421">vs</emphasis>
2.9 × in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Morley" baseAuthorityYear="1913" box="[432,561,547,573]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Symplecis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="421" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="petiolata">
<emphasis box="[432,561,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="421">S. petiolata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), notauli impressed in anterior half (
<emphasis box="[982,1005,547,572]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="421">vs</emphasis>
indistinct in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Morley" baseAuthorityYear="1913" box="[1157,1287,547,573]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Symplecis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="421" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="petiolata">
<emphasis box="[1157,1287,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="421">S. petiolata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), first tergite weakly and evenly bent behind spiracles (
<emphasis box="[635,658,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="421">vs</emphasis>
first tergite distinctly bent behind spiracles in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Morley" baseAuthorityYear="1913" box="[1197,1327,583,609]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Symplecis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="421" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="petiolata">
<emphasis box="[1197,1327,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="421">S. petiolata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and the propodeum without apophyses (
<emphasis box="[511,534,619,644]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="421">vs</emphasis>
propodeum with small round (horizontal) apophyses in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Morley" baseAuthorityYear="1913" box="[1164,1292,619,645]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Symplecis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="421" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="petiolata">
<emphasis box="[1164,1292,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="421">S. petiolata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
